  "prompt": "How is mass and weight related?",
  "response": "Mass and weight are related but distinct concepts:\n\n1. **Mass**:\n   - Mass is a measure of the amount of matter in an object.\n   - It is a scalar quantity and usually measured in kilograms (kg) or grams (g).\n   - Mass is an intrinsic property of an object and does not change based on location.\n\n2. **Weight**:\n   - Weight is the force exerted on an object due to gravity.\n   - It is a vector quantity, which means it has both magnitude and direction.\n   - Weight is calculated by multiplying the mass of an object by the acceleration due to gravity.\n   - The formula for weight (\\(W\\)) is \\(W = m \\cdot g\\), where \\(m\\) is the mass and \\(g\\) is the acceleration due to gravity (approximately \\(9.81 \\, \\text{m/s}^2\\) on the surface of the Earth).\n   - Because weight depends on gravity, it can change based on where the object is in the universe.\n\nIn summary, while mass is a measure of how much matter is present in an object, weight is the gravitational force that acts on that mass. Therefore, an object will have the same mass regardless of its location, but its weight can vary depending on the local gravitational field.",
